{
  "explanation": "While embezzlement is a serious breach of fiduciary duty and trust, sentencing must be proportionate to the specific circumstances of the crime and the defendant's history. The defendant has no prior criminal record and has already demonstrated a willingness to make amends by partially paying back the $25,000 stolen from their employer. These are strong mitigating factors. The outburst from the spectator demanding a 10-year sentence is entirely irrelevant to the proceedings; courts rely on the law and sentencing guidelines, not public emotion or outbursts. Given the first-time nature of the offense, the moderate sum involved, and the ongoing restitution, a lengthy prison term is unnecessary and counterproductive. A brief period of incarceration is appropriate to serve as a deterrent and punishment for the breach of trust, which will be followed by probation and a strict order to complete the remaining restitution.",
  "verdict": 6
}
